<DIV id="content">
        <DIV class="post-header"><H2>September 21, 2005</H2></DIV>      <DIV class="post">        <H3 class="post-title" id="post-9"><A href="http://blog.matthewbass.com/2005/09/21/wiki-on-your-thumb/" rel="bookmark">Wiki on your thumb</A></H3>
                <DIV class="post-content">                        <P>Yesterday I began getting irritated with my Instiki install on my PC at home. Don‚Äôt get me wrong, I like Instiki itself, but having to start it from the command line was getting annoying and I haven‚Äôt yet had time to figure out how to set it up as a Windows service. Add to that the fact that I want to have access to my Wiki from other computers and yet not open up my home network to the world, and you‚Äôll see the dilemma I was facing.</P>
        <P>The ideal thing for me would be to store my Wiki on my USB thumb drive. Instiki‚Äôs data files could theoretically be stored there I suppose, but where would that leave me if I wanted to update my Wiki on a different computer which didn‚Äôt have Instiki installed? My thumb drive is too small to host a copy of Ruby/Rails on it. In desperation, I ran a Google search for ‚Äúwiki on usb drive‚Äù and, behold, <A href="http://www.tiddlywiki.com">TiddlyWiki </A>appeared.</P>
        <P>TiddlyWiki is an experimental ‚Äúmicro-content‚Äù Wiki designed by Jeremy Ruston. It‚Äôs written in HTML, CSS, JavaScript‚Ä¶ and that‚Äôs it. No web server whatsoever is required to run this thing. It‚Äôs basically a self-updating HTML file. Clever! And useful. I can store the HTML page on my thumb drive and access it from any computer with a reasonably up-to-date browser. Theoretically, I could even go a step further and embed the Firefox browser itself on my thumb drive, complete with a custom profile and bookmarks.</P>
        <P>I highly recommend you check out TiddlyWiki if only for the novelty. The install is dead-easy (just save a file to disk) and I found the non-linear navigation structure based on ‚Äútiddles‚Äù (small chunks of information) to be quite logical. I haven‚Äôt seen something this cool since I was first exposed to AJAX!
</P>
